The use of discrete Fourier transforms (DFTs) is a common technique for polynomial multiplication, and the paper presents a unified approach that generalizes all known asymptotically fastest algorithms for this problem. This suggests that the paper could be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), information theory (cs.IT), scientific computing (cs.SC), and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
